WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.890 --> 00:00:04.180
MALE SPEAKER:
--introduce Bjorn Lomborg

00:00:04.180 --> 00:00:05.670
now a long
conversation about how

00:00:05.670 --> 00:00:07.920
to make the world
a better place.

00:00:07.920 --> 00:00:11.246
Most of you may know
Mr. Lomborg's work

00:00:11.246 --> 00:00:13.120
through with the "Skeptical
Environmentalist"

00:00:13.120 --> 00:00:18.650
book that he put out, 2001,
2002, so some years ago.

00:00:18.650 --> 00:00:20.900
Obviously quite
controversial at the time

00:00:20.900 --> 00:00:24.590
and probably to date,
with a focus on climate

00:00:24.590 --> 00:00:27.649
change and how best to address
the problems of climate change.

00:00:27.649 --> 00:00:29.940
And arguing, to some degree,
that climate change per se

00:00:29.940 --> 00:00:32.023
wasn't necessarily the
largest environmental issue

00:00:32.023 --> 00:00:32.870
that we faced.

00:00:32.870 --> 00:00:39.860
He's continued to work in the
spirit of using economic tools

00:00:39.860 --> 00:00:44.190
to try and address questions,
both environmental change

00:00:44.190 --> 00:00:46.909
and developmental challenges
that we face around the world.

00:00:46.909 --> 00:00:48.450
And is currently
working on a project

00:00:48.450 --> 00:00:50.150
to figure out how
the world should best

00:00:50.150 --> 00:00:53.040
spend the next $75
billion dollars that we

00:00:53.040 --> 00:00:56.120
may be investing in the
cause of global development,

00:00:56.120 --> 00:00:58.810
working with the United Nations
and countries around the world.

00:00:58.810 --> 00:01:01.226
We were talking a little bit
around the margins about some

00:01:01.226 --> 00:01:03.580
of the challenges in
getting into that process.

00:01:03.580 --> 00:01:06.100
But I'm delighted to
have him here for what

00:01:06.100 --> 00:01:09.280
I'm sure will be a provocative
and informative discussion.

00:01:09.280 --> 00:01:10.705
So with that, Bjorn.

00:01:10.705 --> 00:01:12.940
BJORN LOMBORG:
Thank you very much.

00:01:12.940 --> 00:01:14.644
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:14.644 --> 00:01:15.500
Thank you.

00:01:15.500 --> 00:01:17.170
It's great to be here.

00:01:17.170 --> 00:01:20.580
And I would love to talk a
little bit about how we're

00:01:20.580 --> 00:01:23.490
going to think about
prioritizing big issues.

00:01:23.490 --> 00:01:26.410
So as you mentioned,
I've worked a lot

00:01:26.410 --> 00:01:28.450
within the environmental area.

00:01:28.450 --> 00:01:30.950
But quite frankly, what we're
doing with the Copenhagen

00:01:30.950 --> 00:01:32.770
Consensus is a broader thing.

00:01:32.770 --> 00:01:35.000
It's essentially to
talk about how do you

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:36.780
spend money to do the most good?

00:01:36.780 --> 00:01:38.980
Where do you get the
biggest bang for your buck?

00:01:38.980 --> 00:01:43.300
So we actually wrote
a book late last year,

00:01:43.300 --> 00:01:46.140
called "How to Spend $75 Billion
to Make the World a Better

00:01:46.140 --> 00:01:46.700
Place."

00:01:46.700 --> 00:01:49.075
If you want a copy, I'm sorry,
I just flew in from China.

00:01:49.075 --> 00:01:50.660
So I'm not carrying
a lot of copies.

00:01:50.660 --> 00:01:53.420
But if you want one,
send an email to Pam

00:01:53.420 --> 00:01:56.150
and we'll send
you a PDF version.

00:01:56.150 --> 00:01:57.900
People said I should
have written the book

00:01:57.900 --> 00:02:01.006
"How to make $75
Billion," but that's

00:02:01.006 --> 00:02:02.380
a totally different
sort of book.

00:02:02.380 --> 00:02:06.460
But this is essentially the kind
of-- if you were Bill Gates.

00:02:06.460 --> 00:02:08.919
We actually do this with
high school students.

00:02:08.919 --> 00:02:12.260
We call it "Bill
Gates for a Day."

00:02:12.260 --> 00:02:15.060
If you had $75 billion dollars,
how would you spend it?

00:02:15.060 --> 00:02:16.685
It turns out that
it's important to say

00:02:16.685 --> 00:02:18.510
you can't spend it on yourself?

00:02:18.510 --> 00:02:21.610
But the idea here is
then to say, where do you

00:02:21.610 --> 00:02:23.080
get the biggest
bang for the buck?

00:02:23.080 --> 00:02:25.260
And their sort of
initial response

00:02:25.260 --> 00:02:27.770
is I can fix all problems.

00:02:27.770 --> 00:02:30.014
They think $75 billion
is a lot of money.

00:02:30.014 --> 00:02:31.430
And then, of course,
they realize,

00:02:31.430 --> 00:02:33.150
no, while it's a
lot of money, it's

00:02:33.150 --> 00:02:35.380
actually not enough
to fix all problems.

00:02:35.380 --> 00:02:37.390
And then they really
want to find out

00:02:37.390 --> 00:02:40.550
how do I spend it in
the best possible way?

00:02:40.550 --> 00:02:43.700
And that's the conversation that
I want to get you involved in.

00:02:43.700 --> 00:02:44.960
We have about an hour.

00:02:44.960 --> 00:02:47.280
And I actually want you
to help me prioritize.

00:02:47.280 --> 00:02:48.510
So I brought some strips.

00:02:48.510 --> 00:02:50.420
I'll distribute them
in just a little bit.

00:02:50.420 --> 00:02:55.150
But to think about how do
we prioritize big issues?

00:02:55.150 --> 00:02:57.440
So if you'll just allow
me-- just let's remember,

00:02:57.440 --> 00:02:59.890
there are lots and lots
of problems in this world.

00:02:59.890 --> 00:03:01.856
And if we talk
about some of them.

00:03:01.856 --> 00:03:03.230
And we probably
should be talking

00:03:03.230 --> 00:03:04.271
about a lot more of them.

00:03:04.271 --> 00:03:05.820
There's about a
billion people that

00:03:05.820 --> 00:03:07.750
don't have clean drinking water.

00:03:07.750 --> 00:03:09.310
Pretty much everyone
in the world

00:03:09.310 --> 00:03:11.980
would be better off if
we didn't have subsidies,

00:03:11.980 --> 00:03:17.540
especially for
agricultural products.

00:03:17.540 --> 00:03:19.580
One of the things
we rarely talk about

00:03:19.580 --> 00:03:22.930
is every year, two new
civil wars, typically

00:03:22.930 --> 00:03:25.120
in places you haven't
even heard of.

00:03:25.120 --> 00:03:28.900
And very often they
get very little

00:03:28.900 --> 00:03:32.230
or no attention in
the global press.

00:03:32.230 --> 00:03:36.920
They cost about $60
billion per civil war.

00:03:36.920 --> 00:03:39.690
Not mostly, as you'd imagine,
because people get killed.

00:03:39.690 --> 00:03:40.900
Yes, they do get killed.

00:03:40.900 --> 00:03:42.920
But because it disrupts
their economies.

00:03:42.920 --> 00:03:46.480
And that essentially means that
people lose a lot of income.

00:03:46.480 --> 00:03:49.710
And that actually means
that they and their babies

00:03:49.710 --> 00:03:51.620
get a lot less health care.

00:03:51.620 --> 00:03:54.530
And that's what really kills
most people in civil wars.

00:03:54.530 --> 00:03:56.060
It's not the actual conflict.

00:03:56.060 --> 00:03:58.440
But it's the fact of
the fallout of all

00:03:58.440 --> 00:04:02.710
of the economic
downturn in these areas.

00:04:02.710 --> 00:04:05.590
Likewise, about
3.5 million people

00:04:05.590 --> 00:04:07.260
die each year from
indoor air pollution.

00:04:07.260 --> 00:04:09.010
And the World Health
Organization actually

00:04:09.010 --> 00:04:15.530
just upped that three weeks ago,
saying it's 4.3 million people.

00:04:15.530 --> 00:04:18.630
So about one in 12 people
that die on this planet,

00:04:18.630 --> 00:04:20.130
die because of
indoor air pollution.

00:04:20.130 --> 00:04:23.470
Basically, lots of poor
people, about 3 billion people,

00:04:23.470 --> 00:04:27.150
cooking and keeping
warm with open fires.

00:04:27.150 --> 00:04:30.010
And 20% of all deaths
in developing countries

00:04:30.010 --> 00:04:32.220
are due to easily curable
infectious diseases.

00:04:32.220 --> 00:04:33.980
The list goes on.

00:04:33.980 --> 00:04:35.990
My point here is
simply to say there

00:04:35.990 --> 00:04:37.900
are lots and lots of problems.

00:04:37.900 --> 00:04:42.390
What should we do with
say the next $75 billion?

00:04:42.390 --> 00:04:44.380
So we're not talking
about recasting

00:04:44.380 --> 00:04:46.510
the entire universe of spending.

00:04:46.510 --> 00:04:48.082
That would be fun
to think about,

00:04:48.082 --> 00:04:49.290
but it's not going to happen.

00:04:49.290 --> 00:04:52.240
And also, our models would not
be very good at handling it,

00:04:52.240 --> 00:04:54.530
if we sort of wanted to
make a radical break.

00:04:54.530 --> 00:04:57.370
Instead, we're talking about
how would you marginally change

00:04:57.370 --> 00:04:57.870
the world?

00:04:57.870 --> 00:05:01.370
And $75 billion is
actually a marginal change

00:05:01.370 --> 00:05:02.210
over four years.

00:05:02.210 --> 00:05:05.390
It's about 10% to 15%
of what the world spends

00:05:05.390 --> 00:05:06.690
on overseas development aid.

00:05:06.690 --> 00:05:09.450
It's a lot less than
what the world spends

00:05:09.450 --> 00:05:12.260
on climate policies.

00:05:12.260 --> 00:05:14.740
So essentially, we're
saying take a small chunk

00:05:14.740 --> 00:05:16.850
or imagine a small
extra chunk and say

00:05:16.850 --> 00:05:17.946
how would you spend that?

00:05:17.946 --> 00:05:19.320
Where would you
do the most good?

00:05:22.090 --> 00:05:24.180
So this is for corporate
social responsibility,

00:05:24.180 --> 00:05:26.580
for philanthropy, for
government spending.

00:05:26.580 --> 00:05:29.850
Right now, our focus
seems to be directed

00:05:29.850 --> 00:05:33.660
by who has the
most cute animals,

00:05:33.660 --> 00:05:35.670
or who have the
most crying babies,

00:05:35.670 --> 00:05:38.120
or who had the
greatest PR groups.

00:05:38.120 --> 00:05:39.940
And why that's very
understandable,

00:05:39.940 --> 00:05:43.420
it's probably not the best
way to deal with this issue.

00:05:43.420 --> 00:05:45.971
I would argue that a
lot of organizations

00:05:45.971 --> 00:05:48.220
who have tried to garner
attention to all their worthy

00:05:48.220 --> 00:05:50.840
subjects, tend to
focus on sort of panic.

00:05:50.840 --> 00:05:51.760
There's an issue here.

00:05:51.760 --> 00:05:52.810
We need to fix it.

00:05:52.810 --> 00:05:54.190
You need to give us money.

00:05:54.190 --> 00:05:55.880
And you sort of
ramp up the message.

00:05:55.880 --> 00:05:57.430
It makes for good PR.

00:05:57.430 --> 00:06:00.130
But it doesn't make
for very good policy.

00:06:00.130 --> 00:06:02.760
So I would argue
we can do better.

00:06:02.760 --> 00:06:04.940
And what we are trying
to do is essentially

00:06:04.940 --> 00:06:08.150
say, well, what's the
most cost-effective way

00:06:08.150 --> 00:06:10.510
to deal with a lot
of these issues?

00:06:10.510 --> 00:06:12.270
That's, of course, a
little more boring.

00:06:12.270 --> 00:06:14.550
It's not as sexy.

00:06:14.550 --> 00:06:17.050
But it just happens
to do a lot more good.

00:06:17.050 --> 00:06:21.400
So really what we tried to
do is to set priorities.

00:06:21.400 --> 00:06:24.920
But setting priorities-- I mean
in principle, everybody agrees.

00:06:24.920 --> 00:06:27.550
Yes, we should do the things
that will do the most good.

00:06:27.550 --> 00:06:30.010
But in reality, of
course, that also

00:06:30.010 --> 00:06:31.860
means when you say
this should come first,

00:06:31.860 --> 00:06:33.730
this should come
second, it also means

00:06:33.730 --> 00:06:35.930
you have to say something
should come last.

00:06:35.930 --> 00:06:37.970
And, of course, that
always annoys people.

00:06:37.970 --> 00:06:41.490
So saying a prioritization
is important also

00:06:41.490 --> 00:06:43.160
mean saying what
shouldn't come first.

00:06:43.160 --> 00:06:46.500
And that inevitably means
you end up annoying people.

00:06:46.500 --> 00:06:49.160
So the people that we typically
have at the top of our list

00:06:49.160 --> 00:06:51.680
think our organization
is the greatest thing

00:06:51.680 --> 00:06:53.930
since sliced bread and
think this is wonderful.

00:06:53.930 --> 00:06:55.800
And they constantly mention it.

00:06:55.800 --> 00:06:59.562
And, of course, the people
who advocate the things

00:06:59.562 --> 00:07:01.270
at the bottom will
just say we're stupid,

00:07:01.270 --> 00:07:04.180
and you shouldn't listen to
us, and all that kind of stuff.

00:07:04.180 --> 00:07:05.160
It's very obvious.

00:07:05.160 --> 00:07:07.970
But it also engenders
a lot of controversy.

00:07:07.970 --> 00:07:10.780
But at the end of the day, I
think we need to ask ourselves

00:07:10.780 --> 00:07:12.030
where can we do the most good?

00:07:12.030 --> 00:07:15.600
And that's really what I want
to talk to you about and have

00:07:15.600 --> 00:07:18.490
you try and help us with doing.

00:07:18.490 --> 00:07:20.914
So these are the 10 challenges
we looked at last year.

00:07:20.914 --> 00:07:22.080
We do this every four years.

00:07:22.080 --> 00:07:25.225
So we did the last one in 2012,
where we get about a hundred

00:07:25.225 --> 00:07:27.197
of the world's top
economists to look across

00:07:27.197 --> 00:07:28.280
all these different areas.

00:07:28.280 --> 00:07:29.196
We have lots of teams.

00:07:29.196 --> 00:07:31.615
I'll talk a little bit
more about the process.

00:07:31.615 --> 00:07:33.240
But fundamentally,
these are the issues

00:07:33.240 --> 00:07:35.230
that we looked at, armed
complex, biodiversity,

00:07:35.230 --> 00:07:37.670
chronic disease, climate
change, education, hunger

00:07:37.670 --> 00:07:40.410
and malnutrition, infectious
diseases, natural disasters,

00:07:40.410 --> 00:07:42.780
population growth, and
water and sanitation.

00:07:42.780 --> 00:07:46.290
I think most people would accept
that, yes, this is definitely

00:07:46.290 --> 00:07:48.984
a very comprehensive list
of the world's big problems.

00:07:48.984 --> 00:07:51.150
You can always imagination
there should be one more.

00:07:51.150 --> 00:07:52.330
We also got to prioritize.

00:07:52.330 --> 00:07:55.680
So we've sort of said we're
only going to look at 10.

00:07:55.680 --> 00:07:57.680
But these are
definitely big issues.

00:07:57.680 --> 00:07:59.400
A typical sort of
journalist question

00:07:59.400 --> 00:08:02.820
is then to say, well, so,
of these big problems,

00:08:02.820 --> 00:08:04.600
which problem is the biggest?

00:08:04.600 --> 00:08:06.600
It's sort of a very
natural question?

00:08:06.600 --> 00:08:08.590
It also turns out to be wrong.

00:08:08.590 --> 00:08:11.110
It's not a well-formed question.

00:08:11.110 --> 00:08:13.680
You can't ask what's the
biggest problem without knowing

00:08:13.680 --> 00:08:14.680
that there's a solution.

00:08:14.680 --> 00:08:16.970
I mean arguably the biggest
problem in the world

00:08:16.970 --> 00:08:18.706
is that we all die.

00:08:18.706 --> 00:08:20.455
But we don't have a
good solution to that.

00:08:20.455 --> 00:08:22.670
And economists would say we
have a severe undersupply

00:08:22.670 --> 00:08:24.120
of immortality.

00:08:24.120 --> 00:08:26.400
But we don't quite
know how to fix that.

00:08:26.400 --> 00:08:29.720
So the issue here is not to
say what's the biggest problem?

00:08:29.720 --> 00:08:32.409
We need to look at what
are the smartest solutions?

00:08:32.409 --> 00:08:35.350
So if you look at armed
conflicts, for instance,

00:08:35.350 --> 00:08:38.400
you could go in and say should
we do conflict prevention?

00:08:38.400 --> 00:08:40.950
Should we have peacekeeping
forces for the UN?

00:08:40.950 --> 00:08:42.236
What are the solutions?

00:08:42.236 --> 00:08:44.110
And then what we tried
to do is to say, well,

00:08:44.110 --> 00:08:46.720
how much with that
solution cost,

00:08:46.720 --> 00:08:48.800
and what's the likelihood
that it will work,

00:08:48.800 --> 00:08:50.977
and how much good would
that solution then do?

00:08:50.977 --> 00:08:53.060
So we're basically saying
how much money would you

00:08:53.060 --> 00:08:55.910
spend, how much good
would you end up doing?

00:08:55.910 --> 00:08:58.720
Likewise for biodiversity, maybe
we should protect more areas.

00:08:58.720 --> 00:09:01.000
Right now, we have
protected about 12%

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:02.140
of the Earth's surface.

00:09:02.140 --> 00:09:03.390
Maybe we should protect more.

00:09:03.390 --> 00:09:04.720
How much will that cost?

00:09:04.720 --> 00:09:05.910
How much good will it do?

00:09:05.910 --> 00:09:08.130
Obviously, it won't
mostly be measured

00:09:08.130 --> 00:09:11.370
in lives saved because it's
not really about human lives.

00:09:11.370 --> 00:09:13.060
But it's about the
fact that we all

00:09:13.060 --> 00:09:16.610
like the idea that there will
be more biodiversity preserved

00:09:16.610 --> 00:09:18.170
for future generations.

00:09:18.170 --> 00:09:20.130
Likewise with chronic
disease, maybe we

00:09:20.130 --> 00:09:22.720
should have a tobacco tax.

00:09:22.720 --> 00:09:25.580
One fun fact is that
in the 20th century,

00:09:25.580 --> 00:09:30.030
we estimated about 100 million
people died from tobacco.

00:09:30.030 --> 00:09:33.820
In the 21st century-- mostly
because China and India are

00:09:33.820 --> 00:09:36.940
smoking like crazy--
we are actually

00:09:36.940 --> 00:09:39.430
estimating on current
trends, we will

00:09:39.430 --> 00:09:42.040
lose about a billion
people to tobacco.

00:09:42.040 --> 00:09:43.880
So maybe we should do
something about that.

00:09:43.880 --> 00:09:45.588
Maybe we should have
a heart attack pill.

00:09:45.588 --> 00:09:46.900
So these are very cheap.

00:09:46.900 --> 00:09:49.520
We know how to deal with
them in developed countries.

00:09:49.520 --> 00:09:51.720
As developing countries
are increasingly

00:09:51.720 --> 00:09:54.066
avoiding infectious
diseases, maybe we

00:09:54.066 --> 00:09:55.940
should start getting
more heart attack pills.

00:09:55.940 --> 00:09:58.800
A lot of people die from a heart
attack in the developing world.

00:09:58.800 --> 00:10:00.690
And on and on, there
are lots and lots

00:10:00.690 --> 00:10:02.780
of solutions for
all of these areas.

00:10:02.780 --> 00:10:04.300
It makes it more complicated.

00:10:04.300 --> 00:10:06.850
But it also makes a lot more
interesting because we're not

00:10:06.850 --> 00:10:10.406
talking about is a problem, a
big problem or a small problem?

00:10:10.406 --> 00:10:11.780
But we're talking
about are there

00:10:11.780 --> 00:10:13.970
good solutions or bad solutions?

00:10:13.970 --> 00:10:16.540
And typically, there are
both good and bad solutions

00:10:16.540 --> 00:10:17.880
to pretty much all of these.

00:10:17.880 --> 00:10:20.510
So it's about finding
the good solutions

00:10:20.510 --> 00:10:22.470
to the big problems
in the world.

00:10:22.470 --> 00:10:25.590
And that's really what I
want to get you involved in.

00:10:25.590 --> 00:10:28.120
So let me just talk a little
bit about how we do this.

00:10:28.120 --> 00:10:31.474
We team up with some of
the world's top economists.

00:10:31.474 --> 00:10:33.140
For instance, on the
infectious disease,

00:10:33.140 --> 00:10:36.130
we worked with Dean
Jamison, who has basically

00:10:36.130 --> 00:10:39.210
written the manual for the
World Health Organization, about

00:10:39.210 --> 00:10:42.190
305 diseases in
the world and what

00:10:42.190 --> 00:10:43.880
their cost and benefits are.

00:10:43.880 --> 00:10:46.190
He has a team of
economists behind him.

00:10:46.190 --> 00:10:48.524
So he goes in and looks at a
lot of different solutions.

00:10:48.524 --> 00:10:50.190
I'm just going to
look at three of them.

00:10:50.190 --> 00:10:52.810
And again, I'm just going to
do them very, very quickly.

00:10:52.810 --> 00:10:56.910
He looks at tuberculosis,
HIV vaccine, and malaria.

00:10:56.910 --> 00:11:00.230
But he doesn't just
say, this is important.

00:11:00.230 --> 00:11:03.560
He says, for every dollar
you spend on tuberculosis

00:11:03.560 --> 00:11:07.940
on the DOTS approach, which
is basically getting people

00:11:07.940 --> 00:11:10.430
medicine, but making
sure they keep taking it.

00:11:10.430 --> 00:11:12.250
I don't know if
you've ever-- I mean

00:11:12.250 --> 00:11:13.590
it's a problem in many places.

00:11:13.590 --> 00:11:16.320
But if you get medicine from
your doctor, once you get good,

00:11:16.320 --> 00:11:19.210
it's hard to remember to
keep taking the medicine far

00:11:19.210 --> 00:11:22.580
out-- a long time after
you've gotten gone well again.

00:11:22.580 --> 00:11:25.022
And that's the problem
was with tuberculosis.

00:11:25.022 --> 00:11:26.730
You actually need to
take your medication

00:11:26.730 --> 00:11:27.850
for a very long time.

00:11:27.850 --> 00:11:30.100
You also need to make sure
that you're actually cured.

00:11:30.100 --> 00:11:34.380
That it wasn't a variant
that was actually

00:11:34.380 --> 00:11:36.150
resistant to the
medicine you got.

00:11:36.150 --> 00:11:39.100
So with all that, and with
the smartest approaches,

00:11:39.100 --> 00:11:42.270
they estimate that for every
dollar spent in tuberculosis,

00:11:42.270 --> 00:11:44.890
you will do about
$15 worth of good.

00:11:44.890 --> 00:11:46.510
That's pretty fantastic.

00:11:46.510 --> 00:11:48.780
On HIV vaccine, they
estimate-- and this

00:11:48.780 --> 00:11:51.910
was the first cost/benefit
for HIV vaccine ever done--

00:11:51.910 --> 00:11:53.660
they estimate that for
every dollar spent,

00:11:53.660 --> 00:11:55.750
you will do about
$11 worth of good.

00:11:55.750 --> 00:11:59.560
For malaria, $1 will
do $35 worth of good.

00:11:59.560 --> 00:12:01.690
Suddenly you get a
very different approach

00:12:01.690 --> 00:12:03.860
to understanding these
are not just good things,

00:12:03.860 --> 00:12:06.200
but some of them are
phenomenal things.

00:12:06.200 --> 00:12:08.850
Of course, we also need to
have a conversation about what

00:12:08.850 --> 00:12:09.950
went into those numbers.

00:12:09.950 --> 00:12:11.440
Do we believe those numbers?

00:12:11.440 --> 00:12:14.200
When you ask an academic,
they'll come up with answers.

00:12:14.200 --> 00:12:16.520
But obviously, they're
not the true answer.

00:12:16.520 --> 00:12:21.520
So we actually asked two other
groups of academics, also

00:12:21.520 --> 00:12:24.520
economists, to give
perspectives on this.

00:12:24.520 --> 00:12:25.990
And basically, he
tells you, yeah,

00:12:25.990 --> 00:12:27.490
but= their model
overestimates this,

00:12:27.490 --> 00:12:30.220
the cost is underestimated
here, all these kinds of things.

00:12:30.220 --> 00:12:33.940
So we actually hear a broad
sort of range of conversations

00:12:33.940 --> 00:12:36.870
on what will work
and what won't.

